UCSD(1)                      UNIX Reference Manual                     UCSD(1)

@{B}NAME@{PLAIN}
     @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN} - a P-code interpreter

@{B}SYNOPSIS@{PLAIN}
     @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN} [@{B}-a@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-g@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-V@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-x@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-b@{PLAIN} @{U}batch-file@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-n@{PLAIN} @{U}SYSTEM-name@{PLAIN}]
          [@{B}-t@{PLAIN} @{U}trace-file@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-w@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-r@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}] [@{B}-f@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}]
          @{U}...@{PLAIN}

@{B}DESCRIPTION@{PLAIN}
     This is the second public release of my P-code interpreter. It does allow
     to run Apple Pascal (an ancient programming environment) on todays comŁ
     puter systems. Although I did many improvements to this code after my
     first release, it still is experimental code.

@{B}OPTIONS@{PLAIN}
     The following options are accepted by @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN}:

     @{B}-a@{PLAIN}    execute the system in Apple compatibility mode.  In Apple compatiŁ
           bility mode, the P-system is initialized using the same addresses
           as the original Apple][ P-system.

     @{B}-g@{PLAIN}    Enter P-code debug mode.

     @{B}-V@{PLAIN}    prints the version number and exits

     @{B}-x@{PLAIN}    Start an @{U}xterm@{PLAIN} for CONSOLE: and SYSTERM:.  Especially useful when
           using the debugger and its messages are output to stdout/stderr.

     @{B}-b@{PLAIN} @{U}batch-file@{PLAIN}
           Starts the system in batch mode.  Input is read from @{U}batch-file@{PLAIN},
           output is written to stdout (unless @{B}-x@{PLAIN} is used).  if '-' is speciŁ
           fied as @{U}batch-file@{PLAIN}, stdin is used.

     @{B}-w@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
           Uses @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN} for I/O on disk volumes in @{U}read-write@{PLAIN} mode.

     @{B}-r@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
           Uses @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN} for I/O on disk volumes in @{U}read-only@{PLAIN} mode.

     @{B}-f@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
           Uses @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN} for I/O on disk volumes in @{U}forget-changes@{PLAIN} mode,
           which discards all changes to the volume, when exiting @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN}.

     @{B}-n@{PLAIN} @{U}SYSTEM-name@{PLAIN}
           Uses @{U}SYSTEM-name@{PLAIN} instead of SYSTEM.PASCAL. In contrast to the origŁ
           inal Apple system, SYSTEM.PASCAL is found on any of the volumes.

     @{B}-t@{PLAIN} @{U}trace-file@{PLAIN}
           Write the P-instructions executed to @{U}trace-file@{PLAIN}. This recorded inŁ
           structions can be compared to a recodring made on an Apple][-emulaŁ
           tor.  If '-' is specified as @{U}trace-file@{PLAIN}, the data is written to
           stdout.

@{B}EXAMPLES@{PLAIN}
     I usually start @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN} with @{U}work.svol@{PLAIN} as #4: in read-write mode and
     @{U}system.svol@{PLAIN} as #5: in read-only mode.

           @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN} @{B}-w@{PLAIN} @{B}work.svol@{PLAIN} @{B}-r@{PLAIN} @{B}system.svol@{PLAIN}

     To use the original Apple Pascal images, APPLE1: on #4:, APPLE2: on #5:
     and APPLE3: on #9: you can execute


           @{B}ucsd@{PLAIN} @{B}-w@{PLAIN} @{B}apple1.dsk@{PLAIN} @{B}-r@{PLAIN} @{B}apple2.dsk@{PLAIN} @{B}-r@{PLAIN} @{B}apple3.dsk@{PLAIN}

@{B}DISK@{PLAIN} @{B}IMAGES@{PLAIN}
     You can make your own set of system disk images (mine are called
     @{U}work.svol@{PLAIN} and @{U}system.svol@{PLAIN}). To create a 1024 block volume in a file
     @{U}my.svol@{PLAIN}, execute

           @{B}rx@{PLAIN} @{B}create@{PLAIN} @{B}my.svol@{PLAIN} @{B}1024@{PLAIN}

     After you have booted the P-system with your system volumes along with
     the new volume, you can use the F(ilers Z(ero command to create an empty
     directory on your volume.

     I put the following files on my volumes:

     WORK:
     SYSTEM.MISCINFO      1    7-Nov-84     6   192   Datafile
     SYSTEM.LIBRARY      28    7-Nov-84     7   512   Datafile
     < UNUSED >         989                35
     2/2 files <listed/in dir>, 35 blocks used, 989 unused, 989 in largest

     SYSTEM:
     SYSTEM.PASCAL       44    3-Sep-85     6   512   Codefile
     SYSTEM.FILER        30    3-Sep-85    50   512   Codefile
     SYSTEM.EDITOR       50    3-Sep-85    80   512   Codefile
     SYSTEM.SYNTAX       12    1-Jul-85   130   512   Textfile
     SYSTEM.COMPILER     78    3-Sep-85   142   512   Codefile
     SYSTEM.LINKER       25    3-Sep-85   220   512   Codefile
     SYSTEM.ASSMBLER     50    3-Sep-85   245   512   Codefile
     6502.OPCODES         2   20-Dec-78   295   208   Datafile
     6502.ERRORS          7   25-Dec-83   297   498   Datafile
     LIBRARY.CODE         8    3-Sep-85   304   512   Codefile
     LIBMAP.CODE         11    3-Sep-85   312   512   Codefile
     ... more stuff

     You will note, there is no @{U}SYSTEM.APPLE@{PLAIN} and no @{U}SYSTEM.CHARSET@{PLAIN} while
     @{U}SYSTEM.PASCAL@{PLAIN} is on the second volume. This P-code interpreter does look
     for @{U}SYSTEM.PASCAL@{PLAIN} on all volumes available, so it does not have to be loŁ
     cated on the system volume.  Only @{U}SYSTEM.LIBRARY@{PLAIN}, @{U}SYSTEM.MISCINFO@{PLAIN} and
     @{U}SYSTEM.WRK.=@{PLAIN} are stored on the system volume.

@{B}DEBUGGER@{PLAIN} @{B}COMMANDS@{PLAIN}
     @{B}p@{PLAIN}     Print evaluation stack
     @{B}d@{PLAIN} [@{U}from@{PLAIN} [@{U}to@{PLAIN}]]
           Dump memory in HEX and ASCII
     @{B}l@{PLAIN} [@{U}SegNo@{PLAIN}] @{U}ProcNo@{PLAIN}
           Disassemble P-code
     @{B}t@{PLAIN}     Dump call stack including local variable and arguments
     @{B}v@{PLAIN}     Dump local variable area of the current procedure/function
     @{B}g@{PLAIN}     Go (start execution)
     @{B}n@{PLAIN}     Execute next instruction, do not trace subroutines.
     @{B}f@{PLAIN}     finish current procedure/function, execution stops at the first inŁ
           struction after returning.
     @{B}r@{PLAIN}     Show registers
     @{B}q@{PLAIN}     Quit interpreter

@{B}SEE@{PLAIN} @{B}ALSO@{PLAIN}
     svolio(1),  svolcvt(1),  "Architecture/Operation of the P-machine", @{U}Apple@{PLAIN}
     @{U}Pascal@{PLAIN} @{U}Operating@{PLAIN} @{U}System@{PLAIN} @{U}Reference@{PLAIN} @{U}Manual@{PLAIN}, Appendix A/B, 1980.  The UCSD
     P-System Museum @{B}http://www.threedee.com/jcm/psystem/index.html@{PLAIN}.

@{B}HISTORY@{PLAIN}
     The first P-system (version I.3), written by Roger T. Sumner, was reŁ
     leased by UCSD in August 1977.  In 1980, Apple Computers released its ApŁ
     ple Pascal, based on UCSD Pascal version II.

@{B}AVAILABILITY@{PLAIN}
     @{B}http://www.klebsch.de/@{PLAIN}

@{B}AUTHOR@{PLAIN}
     Mario Klebsch @{B}<@{PLAIN} @{B}mario@klebsch.de@{PLAIN} @{B}>@{PLAIN}

@{B}BUGS@{PLAIN}
     Lots of functions still missing, e.g. native functions of the Apple PasŁ
     cal System (UNIT APPLESTUFF).

 UCSD P-system                    May 8, 2001                                3
@ENDNODE
@NODE PAGE2 "Page 2"

SVOLIO(1)                    UNIX Reference Manual                   SVOLIO(1)

@{B}NAME@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} - UCSD volume I/O

@{B}SYNOPSIS@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} @{B}-l@{PLAIN} | @{B}-e@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} [@{B}-t@{PLAIN}] @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN} @{U}file@{PLAIN} @{U}...@{PLAIN}

@{B}DESCRIPTION@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} is a utility program to read UCSD volume images.  It can list the
     directory and read files in binary mode as well as in text mode. When
     reading files, the data is written to stdout.  @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN} can be either
     in @{U}.svol@{PLAIN} format or in @{U}.dsk@{PLAIN} format, used by Apple][-emulators.  The @{U}.svol@{PLAIN}
     format does not specify a byte order.  @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} tries to automagically deŁ
     termine the correct byte order

@{B}OPTIONS@{PLAIN}
     The following options are accepted by @{B}svolio@{PLAIN}:

     @{B}-l@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
           show the directory of @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}.

     @{B}-e@{PLAIN} @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}
           show extended directory listing of @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}.

     @{B}-t@{PLAIN}    Read the file using text mode.  In text mode, the first two blocks
           are skiped (they do contain UCSD editor internal data), DLEs and
           line endings are converted.

@{B}EXAMPLES@{PLAIN}
     To read the contents of the volume file @{U}apple1.svol@{PLAIN}, execute

           @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} @{B}-l@{PLAIN} @{B}apple1.dsk@{PLAIN}

     To extract you can use

           @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} @{B}apple1.dsk@{PLAIN} @{B}system.pascal@{PLAIN} @{B}>@{PLAIN} @{B}system.pascal@{PLAIN}

     To take (yet another) view of @{U}GRAFDEMO.TEXT@{PLAIN}, execute

           @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} @{B}-t@{PLAIN} @{B}apple3.dsk@{PLAIN} @{B}grafdemo.text@{PLAIN} @{B}|@{PLAIN} @{B}less@{PLAIN}

@{B}SEE@{PLAIN} @{B}ALSO@{PLAIN}
     ucsd(1),  svolcvt(1),  "File formats/Text files", @{U}Apple@{PLAIN} @{U}Pascal@{PLAIN} @{U}Operating@{PLAIN}
     @{U}System@{PLAIN} @{U}Reference@{PLAIN} @{U}Manual@{PLAIN}, Appendix C, 1980.

@{B}AUTHOR@{PLAIN}
     Mario Klebsch <mario@klebsch.de>

@{B}BUGS@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolio@{PLAIN} should be able to write to @{U}volume-file@{PLAIN}

 UCSD P-system                    May 9, 2001                                1
@ENDNODE
@NODE PAGE3 "Page 3"

SVOLCVT(1)                   UNIX Reference Manual                  SVOLCVT(1)

@{B}NAME@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolcvt@{PLAIN} - UCSD volume I/O

@{B}SYNOPSIS@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolcvt@{PLAIN} < @{U}svol-file@{PLAIN} > @{U}dsk-file@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolcvt@{PLAIN} < @{U}dsk-file@{PLAIN} > @{U}svol-file@{PLAIN}

@{B}DESCRIPTION@{PLAIN}
     @{B}svolcvt@{PLAIN} is a utility program to convert USCD volume images from @{U}.svol@{PLAIN}-
     format to @{U}.dsk@{PLAIN}-format and vice versa. The are needed to specify which
     conversion is needed.

@{B}SEE@{PLAIN} @{B}ALSO@{PLAIN}
     ucsd(1),  svolio(1)

@{B}AUTHOR@{PLAIN}
     Mario Klebsch <mario@klebsch.de>

@{B}BUGS@{PLAIN}
     The size of the volume file must be multiple to 8 blocks (the Apple][
     track size)

     @{B}svolcvt@{PLAIN} does absolutly no checking for errors, the return code always is
     0.

 UCSD P-system                    May 9, 2001                                1
